\begin_layout Section
Majorana ring system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider a system where the embedded nanowire is instead interposed
 between two superconductors of different order parameter phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{L/R}(z)=\Delta_{0}e^{i\phi_{L/R}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us consider that the weak link of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\ll L$
\end_inset

 is at the middle of the wire and that the phase change is abrupt, forming
 a pairing domain wall.
 The order parameter along the wire can then be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(x)=\Delta_{0}\Theta_{L}+\Delta_{0}e^{i\phi}\Theta_{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{R}-\phi_{L}$
\end_inset

, corresponding to the SC Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{H}_{\text{SC}} & =\Delta_{0}\left[\Theta_{L}\tau_{x}+\Theta_{R}\left(\cos\phi\tau_{x}+\sin\phi\tau_{y}\right)\right]\otimes\sigma_{y}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta_{L/R}=\Theta(\pm z-\ell)$
\end_inset

 the Heaviside theta functions.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is set to zero, we recover the previous example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, see that for the particular case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\pi$
\end_inset

 the pairing becomes real, enabling the formation of Majorana fermions at
 the domain wall.
 To demonstrate this, we investigate the existence of zero-energy solution.
 In this case, and according to particle-hole symmetry, the only way to
 define a non-degenerate Nambu operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 is if 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\uparrow/\downarrow}^{\dagger}=\lambda c_{\uparrow/\downarrow}$
\end_inset

 with the constrain 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\pm1$
\end_inset

, effectively reducing the BdG equations to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix differential equation.
 Solving the Hamiltonian's characteristic equation seeking physical exponentiall
y decaying solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\uparrow/\downarrow}(x)\propto e^{\zeta x}$
\end_inset

 one obtains that the type of solution is completely dictated by the sign
 of the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}=\mu^{2}+\Delta_{0}^{2}-V_{\text{Z}}^{2}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the trivial regime and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}\leq0$
\end_inset

 the topological.
